<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-702-512  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 702 512.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  July 23 1990 v9 n15 p57(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Microsystems Engineering tests software for CALS' first phase.andO;(Computer-Aided Acquisition and Logistics Support)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hosinski, Joan M.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsystems Engineering Corp. (product development).andO;Topic:     Government AgencyProduct DevelopmentDefense ContractsProposalElectronic Data InterchangeStandardizationTestingDocument Management Systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Software eases CALS compliance. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Microsystems Engineering Tests Software for CALS' First PhaseandM;BOSTON -- Microsystems Engineering Corp. has begun testing Computer-AidedAcquisition and Logistics Support (CALS) software for MS-DOS and DigitalEquipment Corp.'s VMS.andM;Defense contractors already should be submitting proposals in the CALSformat, but the Defense Department has been &quot;offering some relief becausepeople did not get ready in time,&quot; said John Graves, president and chiefexecutive officer of Microsystems Engineering of Hoffman Estates, Ill.andM;&quot;Companies are beginning to feel the pressure and it won't be long before thedoor shuts&quot; as more CALS products hit the market, he said late last month atthe Dexpo East conference.andM;The first phase of the Defense Department CALS program covers documentretrieval, but Microsystems Engineering's CALS Software Submission (CSS)system will satisfy future CALS text search and retrieval enhancements.andP;  CSSwill let the user tag down to the word level in documents, instead of to thecurrent paragraph level.andM;Database and text retrieval software from a business partner, Paralog ofStockholm, Sweden, will help the company meet Phase II CALS documentmanagement requirements, Graves said.andP;  The software provides control,security and access to the document.andM;CSS also includes an XGML, engine from Software Exoterica Corp. of Ottawa,Canada.andM;The engine performs Standard Generalized Markup Language (SGML) tagging andparsing, which validates sections of a document as writers and editors workon the document.andP;  &quot;This approach was selected and packaged so that futureimprovements and modifications could be easily added to follow the evolvingCALS definition,&quot; Graves said.andM;Microsystems Engineering, of course, advises clients to use its Mass-11technical document processing software for text creation and editing, but theCALS system imports text in ASCII or IBM's Document Content Architectureformats.andM;Beta CSS software will be available Sept. 1, and late in the year productionshipments will begin.andP;  The system starts at $8,000.andM;Several CALS products are offered by publishing companies, but those CALSproducts have an &quot;open loop&quot; because the author does not get to review thedocument after it has passed through the SGML editor and been stored onmagnetic media, Graves said.andP;  CSS delivers the primary file back to theauthor.andM;CSS is &quot;attractive financially for installations that already have VAXes andPCs,&quot; Graves said.andP;  &quot;It's a myth that you have to start from scratch,hardware and software-wise, to become CALS compliant.&quot;andM;The Food and Drug Administration and the Housing and Urban DevelopmentDepartment are having a &quot;lot of high-level conversations&quot; about adhering toCALS standards, Graves said.andM;Contact Carol Karels of Microsystems Engineering Corp., tel.andP;  201-592-6633.andO;</TEXT></DOC>